Data description: The Boston data frame has 506 rows and 14 columns.

This data frame contains the following columns:

crim - per capita crime rate by town.
zn - proportion of residential land zoned for lots over 25,000 sq.ft.
indus - proportion of non-retail business acres per town.
chas - Charles River dummy variable (= 1 if tract bounds river; 0 otherwise).
nox - nitrogen oxides concentration (parts per 10 million).
rm - average number of rooms per dwelling.
age - proportion of owner-occupied units built prior to 1940.
dis - weighted mean of distances to five Boston employment centres.
rad - index of accessibility to radial highways.
tax - full-value property-tax rate per $10,000$.
ptratio - pupil-teacher ratio by town.
black - $1000(Bk - 0.63)^2$ where Bk is the proportion of blacks by town.
lstat - lower status of the population (percent).
medv - median value of owner-occupied homes in $1000s$.

Standardization¶

In [9]:
means = features.mean(axis=0)
stds = features.std(axis=0)

scaled_features = (features - means) / stds

In [25]:
def calculate_vif(X):
    vif_data = pd.DataFrame()
    vif_data["feature"] = X.columns
    vif_data["VIF"] = [variance_inflation_factor(X.values, i)
                            for i in range(len(X.columns))]

    return vif_data

Graph of cost predictions from a variable that has the highest modulo coefficient (lstat)¶

Lower status of the population is negatively correlated with target. The graph shows a good linear correlation

The model shows good R-squared metrics and quite well predicts the median value of a house according to the given features.

Additional part¶

Above it was shown that the lower status of the population correlates well with the average cost of a house. Therefore, in order to maximize the price of a house for sale, it is necessary to build a house in an area with a high population status.

In [59]:
ax = sns.scatterplot(x = X["rm"], y = target)
ax.set(xlabel='Average number of rooms per dwelling',
       ylabel='Median value of owner-occupied homes in  1000s',
       title='Graph of the dependence of the value of the house on the average number of rooms per dwelling')
plt.show()

So, the next feature that have a good correlation with target is average number of rooms per dwelling.
But with an increase in the number of rooms, the cost of building one apartment increases, so I’m not sure if this is the point that you should focus on in the first place in order to maximize the price for the house.

Let's make conclusions:¶

To maximize the value of a house it is nesessary to build in an area with:

  1. high population status
  2. low share of non-retail business, or minimize their number in the area that you are building
  3. low full-value property-tax rate
  4. the least nitrogen oxides concentration
  5. minimum level of crime
